{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626785"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17097"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17097"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.76,0.16,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5100"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23172"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a three-month history of increased thirst and frequent urination. Her random blood glucose is 12.8 mmol/L (3.9-7.8) and glycated haemoglobin is 8.2% (4.0-6.0). After lifestyle modifications, she is prescribed Metformin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of Metformin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits glucose reabsorption in kidneys","Increases glucagon secretion","Decreases hepatic glucose production","Increases insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells","Delays gastric emptying"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of metformin is \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs through activation of AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK), which reduces gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis in the liver. Metformin is a biguanide, meaning its chemical structure contains two linked guanide groups, which is essential for its therapeutic action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits glucose reabsorption in kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitors, which are a different class of diabetes medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases glucagon secretion\u003C/strong\u003E: Metformin reduces glucagon levels, as elevated glucagon would increase blood glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E: unlike sulfonylureas, insulin release from the pancreas is not directly stimulated by Metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelays gastric emptying\u003C/strong\u003E: while Metformin may cause gastrointestinal side effects, this is not its therapeutic mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional beneficial effects of Metformin include increased peripheral glucose uptake in skeletal muscle and decreased intestinal glucose absorption. These effects contribute to its overall glucose-lowering action.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metformin reduces hepatic glucose production by activating AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK).","Metformin increases peripheral glucose uptake in skeletal muscle through insulin-dependent mechanisms.","Metformin decreases intestinal glucose absorption, contributing to its blood glucose-lowering effects.","Metformin belongs to the biguanide class of medications, characterised by two linked guanide groups."],"references":["Weinberg Sibony R, Segev O, Dor S, Raz I. Drug Therapies for Diabetes. Int J Mol Sci. 2023;24(24):17147. Published 2023 Dec 5. doi:10.3390/ijms242417147","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17097"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T21:25:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:25:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"d